AllLife Bank Campaign Project¶

Context¶

All Life Bank wants to look at its customrs more in depth. Based on this insight, the marketing team will run campaigns that are personalized to customers. The Operations team also wants to improve on services recieved poorly and improve the delivery model.

Objective¶

  1. Look into the data, make clusters of customers based on their spending and previous bank interaction.
  2. Look into the clusters and determine differences
  3. Reccomend the banl on how to better marketing and services to these customers

Notes on EDA¶

  • Avg credit limit is a skewed to the right
  • total credit cards, total calls made, and total bank visits all look relatively as though they have a gaussian distribution
  • total visits online is skewed right as well
  • there is a strong positive correlation between total credit cards and and avg credit limit (r = 0.61)
  • there is a strong posiitve correlation between total online vists and average credit limit (r = 0.55)
  • there is a string negative correlation between total calls mad and total number of credit cards (r = -0.65)
  • there is a strong negative correlation between total online visits and total bank visits (r = -0.55)
  • there is a weak negative correlation between total online visits and average credit limit
  • there is a weak positive correlation between total bank vists and total number of credit cards

K Means Clustering¶

In [19]:
#Finding optimal no. of clusters by K Means Clustering
from scipy.spatial.distance import cdist
clusters=range(1,10)
meanDistortions=[]

for k in clusters:
    model=KMeans(n_clusters=k)
    model.fit(scaled_data)
    prediction=model.predict(scaled_data)
    meanDistortions.append(sum(np.min(cdist(scaled_data, model.cluster_centers_, 'euclidean'), axis=1)) / scaled_data.shape[0])


plt.plot(clusters, meanDistortions, 'bx-')
plt.xlabel('k')
plt.ylabel('Average distortion')
plt.title('Selecting k with the Elbow Method')
Out[19]:
Text(0.5, 1.0, 'Selecting k with the Elbow Method')
In [20]:
#Find the optimum K with Silhouette score

sil_score = []
cluster_list = list(range(2, 10))
for n_clusters in cluster_list:
    clusterer = KMeans(n_clusters=n_clusters)
    preds = clusterer.fit_predict((scaled_data))
    # centers = clusterer.cluster_centers_
    score = silhouette_score(scaled_data, preds)
    sil_score.append(score)
    print("For n_clusters = {}, silhouette score is {}".format(n_clusters, score))
 
plt.plot(cluster_list, sil_score)

Hierarchical data¶

In [24]:
# list of distance metrics
distance_metrics = ["euclidean", "chebyshev", "mahalanobis", "cityblock"]

# list of linkage methods
linkage_methods = ["single", "complete", "average", "weighted"]

high_cophenet_corr = 0
high_dm_lm = [0, 0]

for dm in distance_metrics:
    for lm in linkage_methods:
        Z = linkage(scaled_data, metric=dm, method=lm)
        c, coph_dists = cophenet(Z, pdist(scaled_data))
        print(
            "Cophenetic correlation for {} distance and {} linkage is {}.\n".format(
                dm.capitalize(), lm, c
            )
        )
        if high_cophenet_corr < c:
            high_cophenet_corr = c
            high_dm_lm[0] = dm
            high_dm_lm[1] = lm

for lm in linkage_methods:
    Z = linkage(scaled_data, metric="euclidean", method=lm)
    c, coph_dists = cophenet(Z, pdist(scaled_data))
    print("Cophenetic correlation for {} linkage is {}.".format(lm, c))
    if high_cophenet_corr < c:
        high_cophenet_corr = c
        high_dm_lm[0] = "euclidean"
        high_dm_lm[1] = lm

In [27]:
#Dendograms:

# list of linkage methods
linkage_methods = ["single", "complete", "average", "centroid", "ward", "weighted"]

# lists to save results of cophenetic correlation calculation
compare_cols = ["Linkage", "Cophenetic Coefficient"]
compare = []

# to create a subplot image
fig, axs = plt.subplots(len(linkage_methods), 1, figsize=(15, 30))

# We will enumerate through the list of linkage methods above
# For each linkage method, we will plot the dendrogram and calculate the cophenetic correlation
for i, method in enumerate(linkage_methods):
    Z = linkage(scaled_data, metric="euclidean", method=method)

    dendrogram(Z, ax=axs[i])
    axs[i].set_title(f"Dendrogram ({method.capitalize()} Linkage)")

    coph_corr, coph_dist = cophenet(Z, pdist(scaled_data))
    axs[i].annotate(
        f"Cophenetic\nCorrelation\n{coph_corr:0.2f}",
        (0.80, 0.80),
        xycoords="axes fraction",
    )

    compare.append([method, coph_corr])

# list of distance metrics
distance_metrics = ["chebyshev", "cityblock"]

# list of linkage methods
linkage_methods = ["average", "weighted"]

# to create a subplot image
fig, axs = plt.subplots(
    len(distance_metrics) + len(distance_metrics), 1, figsize=(10, 30)
)

i = 0
for dm in distance_metrics:
    for lm in linkage_methods:
        Z = linkage(scaled_data, metric=dm, method=lm)

        dendrogram(Z, ax=axs[i])
        axs[i].set_title("Distance metric: {}\nLinkage: {}".format(dm.capitalize(), lm))

        coph_corr, coph_dist = cophenet(Z, pdist(scaled_data))
        axs[i].annotate(
            f"Cophenetic\nCorrelation\n{coph_corr:0.2f}",
            (0.80, 0.80),
            xycoords="axes fraction",
        )
        i += 1

Insights on Clusters made from Hierarchical Clustering¶

  • Cluster 1:

    • average credit limit
    • average amount of credit cards
    • average amount of total calls made
    • high number of in person bank visits
    • low amount of online bank visits

  • Cluster 2:

    • low credit limit
    • low amount of credit cards
    • high number of calls made
    • average amount of in person bank visits
    • average amounts of online visits

  • Cluster 3:

    • high credit limit
    • high amount of credit cards
    • low number of calls made
    • low amount of in person bank visits
    • high amounts of online visits

Insights on Clusters between K Means Clustering and Hierarchical Clustering¶

  • Hierachical cluster 1 is the same as cluster 1 from K Means Cluster
  • Hierachical cluster 2 is the same as cluster 2 from K Means Cluster

  • Hierachical cluster 3 is the same as cluster 3 from K Means Cluster

  • All of the clusters were the same in both methods

Business Insights¶

  • There are 3 clusters of customers in the database:
    • The first cluster is made up of customers who spend an average amount of money, have an average amount of credit cards, and visit the bank in person very often, but do not go online.
    • The second cluster is made up of customers who do not spend a lot of money, have few credit cards, call the bank often, and have an average amount of in person and online back visits.
    • The third cluster is made up of customers who spend a lot of money, have many credit cards, do not visit the bank in person, but visit the online site often.

  • Customers who go into the bank in person usually spend an average amount and have an average amount of credit cards. Marketing campaigns targeting these spending traits and visiting patterns will bring these customers the most satisfaction.

  • Customers who spend the least money also call the banks most often. Marketing campaings that focus on customers who do not spend much money and have few cards should have a better phone call experiences to bring these customers the most satisfaction

  • Customers who spend the most money had a high number of online vists. Marketing campaings focusing on making the website more user friendly for high spenders will bring the most satisfaction to these group of customers.
